# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: applecrab
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:applecrab/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:applecrab/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:applecrab/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:applecrab/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:applecrab/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:applecrab/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:applecrab/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:applecrab/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:applecrab/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:applecrab/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:applecrab/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:applecrab/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:applecrab/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:applecrab/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:applecrab/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:applecrab/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:applecrab/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:applecrab/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:applecrab/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Albert Felix Etter was born near Shingle Springs in El Dorado County, California, on November 27, 1872.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] He was one of ten surviving children of the Swiss-born Benjamin Etter (d.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Around 1876 the family moved to Humboldt County, where Benjamin acquired a farm near Ferndale and became the first person to grow lentils in the county.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Albert's German-born mother, Wilhelmina (Kern) Etter (d.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] 1913) was skilled at cultivating plants, and Etter showed a talent for hybridizing plants in childhood, working with apples, peaches, dahlias, and strawberries by the time he was twelve.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] He attended public school and by the end of his teens was looking for a site where he could continue his plant-breeding experiments.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] On a fishing trip to the Mattole River Valley, he found a section of land above Bear Creek and in 1894 he staked a claim to it.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] This area along the Pacific coast in the King Range has wet winters and hot summers, and Etter later attributed his success partly to his choice of location.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] The site where Etter developed his ranch was subsequently named after him, first as Etter and then as Ettersburg.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Etter managed the ranch with three of his brothers, George, Fred, and August; and another four of his siblings also lived nearby.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] While Etter focused on plant breeding, his brothers oversaw other kinds of farming and stockkeeping operations.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] The ranch holdings, operated under the business name Etter Brothers, eventually reached 800 acres in size.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Etter wrote about his "Mountain Home of Sciences" in 1907.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Although the Etter Brothers firm and the Ettersburg Experimental Place became internationally known among plant breeders, and Etter renowned as "the Luther Burbank of Humboldt County", they never made more than a modest living from the land.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] For one thing, they were far removed from the main trucking and rail routes, and for another, new plant hybrids were not protected by the patent system until 1930.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Etter was sometimes compared to Luther Burbank.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1907 it was noted that Etter '... resents such appellations as "wizard" and "Burbank of Humboldt,” and declared that plain Albert Etter is a good enough title to go by.' In 1908, Etter visited Luther Burbank in Santa Rosa.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Burbank commented that Santa Rosa was not favorable for apples.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Etter became known for his insistence on the value of using unimproved parent material, often taken from wild strains, and he frequently made 'wide' crosses between widely divergent genetic types.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In his work with strawberries, he showed other breeders the value of the beach strawberry (*Fragaria chiloensis*) as a source of germplasm conveying vigor, productivity, flavor, and disease resistance.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] He also worked in a more minor way with *F. virginiana* species.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] The Pacific Rural Press described his methods for strawberries and other plants in 1912.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] By 1910, Ettersburg 121 had become the leading variety in the Willamette Valley, Oregon, because its firm flesh, high color, and strong flavor meant that it canned well.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1912, you could get a gift of a dozen plants with your subscription to the Pacific Rural Press.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1914, the press anticipated Etter's strawberry exhibit at the 1915 world's fair.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1915, Etter exhibited his strawberries at the Panama-Pacific International Exposition.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] "Among the other valuable features of the California Section were the strawberries of Albert Etter of Briceland, Humboldt County, California.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] By 1920, Etter's catalog showcased over 50 new varieties, some of which achieved limited commercial success.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] None are commercially important today, although their germplasm continues in a number of modern cultivars.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1928, he donated all his strawberry material to the University of California, where his Ettersburg 121 became an ancestor of various commercially important varieties.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1899 it was reported that Albert Etter, with the help of the University of California, was establishing a private experimental orchard near Briceland.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Etter started with 62 varieties in 1898 and received several hundred more varieties in 1899.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Years later Etter wrote about apple breeding at Ettersberg in the Pacific Rural Press (1922) He said that "the anniversary of my arrival here to begin operations was afterward made National Apple Day—the 17th of October." The Pacific Rural Press reported that he had 10,000 varieties of apples.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] He started with almost 600 apple varieties.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] These were gathered from America and Europe, with the help of Charles Howard Shinn, when he was Inspector of California Experiment Stations, between 1890 and 1901.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1907 and 1909 a number of Etter's apple varieties were offered in the annual distribution of seeds and plants from the University of California.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1919 it was reported that he had hybridized the native California crabapple with the Oregon crabapple and had created a fruit one inch in diameter with a brilliant color.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1924, the Livermore Journal reported that he was about to introduce 75 different apple varieties.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In the late 1920s, Etter shifted his attention to apple breeding, using scion wood gleaned from a number of sources including the University of California.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] He felt that the west coast climate called for new kinds of apples, and he began experimenting with wide crosses, especially between apples and crabapples.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Although many of his apple strains have been lost, those that survive include Pink Pearl, the best-known of his unusual series of some two dozen pink- and red-fleshed cultivars based on a European apple called Surprise (itself probably a descendant of *Malus niedzwetskyana*).
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Some eastern and midwestern breeders, including Liberty Hyde Bailey and Charles Downing had already made some experiments with Surprise and been unhappy with the results, but Etter found that it worked better as part of a west-coast breeding program.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] By 1928, Etter was far enough along in his breeding experiments to publish a preliminary report in the *Pacific Rural Press*, where he wrote about two of his pink-fleshed cultivars, the Redflesh Winter Banana and a nameless seedling that, by its description, might have been Pink Pearl.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Subsequently, the midwestern breeder Niels Ebbesen Hansen worked on breeding red-fleshed apples and crabapples, expressing disappointment when he found that Etter had beaten him to the punch.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Although not all of Etter's Surprise descendants were successful, the best of them shared a pronounced aromatic quality that appears to be linked to the anthocyanin pigmentation that gives the flesh its distinctive pinkish and reddish tones.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1930 Etter introduced a flavorful juicy bright red red-fleshed apple at an apple show in Eureka.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Several boxes were sent to hotels throughout the country.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In 1940, Etter began a partnership with George Roeding Jr., the owner of the California Nursery Company in Niles (now a district of Fremont, California).
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Their goal was to patent and market Etter's best apple varieties.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] The California Nursery Company introduced six Etter varieties in its 1944 catalog – Pink Pearl and five apples with regular non-pigmented flesh (Alaska, All Gold, Humboldt Crab, Jonwin, and Wickson).
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] A seventh apple, Crimson Gold, was introduced in the 1947 catalog.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] The 1970 catalog carried only five varieties of Etter's apples: Alaska, Etter's Gold, Jonwin, Pink Pearl, and Wickson.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] A flyer with "Distinctive New Recipes...for the Apples of Albert Etter" was provided in the 1945 catalog.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Recipes were by Robert Stoney Mayock who was a winemaker (Los Amigos Vineyards in Irvington), amateur chef, gourmet, and food columnist.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Etter also experimented with breeding over a hundred varieties of forage plants, grasses, and clovers.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] His research showed that some of the large white clovers from southern Europe were suitable for Humboldt County dairy farmers to use for forage because they put on a great deal of growth during the winter.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] He also undertook some experiments with tree nut crops such as English walnuts, chestnuts and filberts.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Etter was a member of the California Nurserymen's Association and the American Pomological Society, and he was president of the Ettersburg Farm Center (a branch of the Humboldt County Farm Bureau).
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] His wife Katharine (born Katharine McCormick in 1891) outlived him by nearly three decades, dying in 1979.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] In the 1970s, apple fancier Ram Fishman visited the remains of Etter's experimental orchard and found over one hundred trees still thriving.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] On many of these trees, multiple test varieties were represented, often by a single grafted branch.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] Fishman ultimately located about half of Etter's pink-fleshed varieties in the test orchard and in nearby areas, and in 1983 he founded the Greenmantle Nursery to make seven of them available to the public.
[src:applecrab/albert-etter] They were given new names since the old names could not be firmly determined and are marketed under the Rosetta series title.
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:applecrab/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:applecrab/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:applecrab/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:applecrab/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:applecrab/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:applecrab/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:applecrab/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:applecrab/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:applecrab/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:applecrab/applecrab] Applecrabs are sometimes distinguished from apples if the fruit diameter is less than 5 cm (2 in).
[src:applecrab/applecrab] Director of the Canadian Central Experimental Farm William Saunders (1836–1914) produced a number of such hybrids as part of an effort to develop good-quality eating apples for the Canadian prairies by crossing the domesticated apple cultivars with selected winter-hardy crabapple species.
[src:applecrab/applecrab] A separate project was initiated by C.S.
[src:applecrab/applecrab] Crandall of the University of Illinois to breed scab-resistant apples by introducing the *VF*gene from the crabapple *Malus floribunda*.
[src:applecrab/applecrab] His work has been continued by the PRI disease resistant apple breeding program with great success.
[src:applecrab/applecrab] Another type of applecrab breeding program stems from *Malus niedzwetskyana*, a red-fleshed crabapple, a few of which can still be found in Siberia and the Caucasus.
[src:applecrab/applecrab] It has been used by modern breeders to breed some red-leaved, red-flowered, and red-fruited domesticated apples and crabapples.
[src:applecrab/applecrab] One example is 'Surprise', a pink-fleshed apple that was brought to the United States by German immigrants around 1840 and was later used by horticulturist Albert Etter to breed some 30 pink- and red-fleshed varieties, the best-known of which is 'Pink Pearl'.
[src:applecrab/applecrab] His efforts resulted in the 'Almata' apple and the 'Hopa' crabapple, among other varieties.
[src:applecrab/applecrab] Some of these apples, as well as *M. niedzwetskyana* itself, are being used for small-scale commercial production of rosé apple ciders.
